  "prompt": "What is the best iOS calendar app that allows you to cross off EVENTS as you go through the day?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, there isn't a native or universally \"best\" iOS calendar app that offers a dedicated \"cross off\" feature for *events*. Most calendar apps focus on showing what's upcoming.\n\nHowever, there are a few approaches and apps you can use to achieve a similar effect:\n\n**1. Using Task Management Apps with Calendar Integration:**\n\n*   **TickTick (Highly Recommended):** TickTick is a popular task manager that integrates seamlessly with iOS calendars.  You can create tasks within TickTick, assign them a due date/time, and they'll appear in your calendar.  As you complete each task, you can \"check it off\" in TickTick, visually marking it as done.  The key benefit is its robust task management features alongside calendar viewing.\n*   **Todoist:** Similar to TickTick, Todoist is a powerful task manager with calendar integration.  You create tasks, assign due dates, and mark them as complete.  It syncs with your calendar and when you mark a task as done in Todoist, it's visually represented as completed.\n*   **Microsoft To Do:** Microsoft's task management app, To Do, integrates with Outlook Calendar.  You can add tasks with deadlines, and when marked complete, they appear as done on your calendar.\n*   **Any.do:** Any.do is another excellent task manager with strong calendar features. You can add tasks, set deadlines, and mark them as complete, visually updating the tasks linked to your calendar.\n\n**Why Task Managers are a Good Solution:**\n\n*   **Flexibility:**  You can add more details to tasks than you typically would to a calendar event (subtasks, notes, attachments, etc.).\n*   **Clear Visual Indication:** The \"checked off\" or completed task is highly visible, making it easy to track your progress.\n*   **Task Management Features:** Benefit from reminders, recurring tasks, prioritization, and collaboration features.\n\n**2. Using Calendar Apps with Workarounds:**\n\n*   **Fantastical:** While it doesn't have a cross-off feature, Fantastical is considered by many to be the best overall calendar app for iOS.  You could *edit* events after they occur to add a prefix like \"[DONE]\" or a checkmark emoji (\u2705). This isn't ideal but provides a visual indication of completion.\n\n**3.  Calendar Apps with Status Indicators:**\n\n*   **Google Calendar:** While not a \"cross-off,\" Google Calendar allows you to change an event's color.  You could create a custom color specifically to mark completed events.  This offers a visual cue of completion.\n\n**4. Dedicated Checklist Apps with Calendar Functionality:**\n\n*   Some checklist apps might have calendar views built in, allowing you to see your checklists alongside your calendar. If the checklists can be synced into your main calendar, you could create your list as calendar events, then check those off to see the results in your default calendar. This is a less ideal solution.\n\n**Key Considerations when Choosing:**\n\n*   **Calendar Integration:**  How well does the app sync with your existing iOS calendars (iCloud, Google, Outlook, etc.)?\n*   **Task Management Features:**  Do you need advanced task management features like subtasks, recurring tasks, collaboration, and prioritization?\n*   **Ease of Use:**  How intuitive is the app to use?\n*   **Cost:**  Is the app free, a one-time purchase, or a subscription?\n\n**In summary, I highly recommend starting with TickTick or Todoist. They offer the best combination of calendar integration and task management features with clear visual cues for marking events (as tasks) complete.**  Experiment with the free versions to see which one fits your workflow best. While a dedicated \"cross off\" feature for standard calendar *events* is rare, these workarounds will provide a similar and often more powerful solution for managing your day.\n",
